Place @butter{2%tbsp} (4 TBSP for 4 servings) in a small #microwave-safe bowl{}; bring
to room temperature.

Wash and dry all produce.

Halve, peel, and finely chop @yellow onion{1}. Trim, peel, and dice @carrots{6%oz}.
Dice @Roma tomato{1}.

> TIP: Use a large pot for 4 servings.

Heat a large drizzle of @vegetable oil{} in a medium #pot over medium-high heat.
Add @Italian chicken sausage mix{9%oz}; cook, breaking up meat into pieces,
until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Transfer to a #plate.

To same pot over medium-high heat, add another drizzle of oil, onion, carrots,
and a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook, stirring occasionally, until slightly
softened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Stir in diced tomato, @tomato paste{1.5%oz}, @Tuscan Heat Spice{1%tbsp}, and half
the @garlic powder{1%tsp} (you'll use the rest in the next step). Cook until
fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir in @cannellini beans{13.4%oz} and their liquid, @chicken stock concentrate{2},
and @water{3.5%cups} (6 cups for 4 servings).

Cover pot and bring to a boil, then uncover and stir in cooked sausage.
Reduce heat to medium and simmer until soup is slightly thickened,
~{7-10%minutes}.

While soup simmers, heat broiler to high.

Stir remaining garlic powder into softened butter until combined; season with
a pinch of salt and pepper.

> TIP: If butter isn't yet softened, microwave for 10-15 seconds.

Halve @ciabatta bread{1}, then cut on a diagonal to create triangles. Place cut
sides up on a #baking sheet{} and spread with garlic butter.

> TIP: For easy cleanup, line baking sheet with aluminum foil first.

Sprinkle with half the @Parmesan cheese{1/4%cup} (save the rest for serving).

Broil until golden brown, ~{2-4%minutes}.

> TIP: Watch carefully to avoid burning.

Taste soup and season generously with salt and pepper.

> TIP: If soup is too thick, add a splash or two of water.

Divide soup between #bowls{} and sprinkle with remaining Parmesan.
Serve with cheesy garlic ciabatta toasts on the side.